I like a lot of this (historical skips are my jam) but felt compelled to downvote for two reasons.

1. Why did Carthage have this in the first place? I don't necessarily expect a full explanation but with such an out there alt-history premise I'd at least like a hint. The bit with Bumaro feels like it should have been that hint, but it more comes off as him feeling the same bafflement I do.

2. Carthage losing with this breaks my suspension of disbelief hardcore. This is a 1000 feet tall mech. Pre-marian Roman legions would have as much chance vs this as a Chihuahua puppy would have against a fully grown grizzly. Even with Trebuchets (which didn't come into Europe for 800 more years after these events and didn't become commonplace for like 1400 years) this seems really improbable. Early siege engines could wear down stone walls (between 20-40 ft in height) over weeks/months of bombardment and were incredibly inaccurate. No way they took down a moving, metal target the size of the Empire State Building. Hell, I'm not sure Napoleonic artillery could manage it.





