+Open

-Close


I like the way it quietly expands possibilities surrounding the Church of the Broken God by giving a Mekhane-ish anomaly to a group that doesn't seem to serve Mekhane. I like how the Romans effectively won the same way they beat Hannibal in actual history—brains, guts, and an absolute refusal to surrender. I like the subtle implication that (assuming I'm not reading more into this than is actually there) the Fall of Hyperion was what got the ball rolling on what eventually became the Foundation we know today.

The premise is somewhat basic, yes, but I think this is one of those cases where the execution is good enough that it's okay to have a basic premise.

That said, it doesn't really work as horror for me. I can see the buildup, and that was effective, but when the time came I was too annoyed at the unnamed-figure-that's-probably-Hasdrubal failing to understand he passage of time to actually be frightened. I'm sure it makes sense in-universe, and this is all sorts of subjective, but it is what it is.




Overall, I'd say that the subjective nature of the issues I have with it, coupled with how much I like the rest, push me over into +1 territory.







